The Prague Stock Exchange plunges into the red at close of business.
After the steep fall in the morning, the Prague Stock Exchange was able to correct losses.
Transactions in ČEZ shares reached almost half of normal day-to-day business.
The Prague Stock Exchange followed Monday&#39;s slump right at the start of Tuesday&#39;s trading, dropping another six percentage points.
This time the reason for the slump was Wall Street.
In the Czech Republic, too, the reaction of the market to the result of the vote in the American House of Representatives, which had refused to support a stabilization plan for the local financial sector, can be seen.
Fall in stocks in Asia
Shares on the stock exchanges in Asia experienced a dramatic fall on Tuesday, although the indices were able to compensate for some of the losses during the course of the day.
The Hong Kong Hang Seng Stock Exchange index slipped nearly four percentage points during the business day but later erased some of the losses, narrowing the decline to about 2.5 percent.
The Hang Seng China Enterprises index, which tracks the movement of Chinese stocks on the Hong Kong Stock Exchange, fell 3.8 percent, while markets in Shanghai were closed.
Shares on the Sydney Stock Exchange fell more than 5 percent but then narrowed losses to 4.3 percent.
The stock market in Taiwan fell by 3.6 percent according to the local index.
&quot;The timing of the US bailout is uncertain and will affect financial markets worldwide,&quot; said Hong Kong Monetary Authority chief Joseph Yam.
Despite being part of China, Hong Kong determines its monetary policy itself, i.e. independently of the Chinese central bank.
Interest rates in Hong Kong are at the same level as those in the United States.
According to Australian Prime Minister Kevin Rudd, American lawmakers should return to the negotiating table as soon as possible and pass the draft financial system support.
Otherwise there is a risk that other countries would also be affected by the slump.
A bloodbath of American stocks
The US House of Representatives on Monday rejected a plan to support the financial system, which would cost up to $700 billion (almost CZK 12 trillion).
Lawmakers ignored President George Bush&#39;s request to support the plan.
In Bush&#39;s view, the plan would address the root causes of the financial crisis and thus help stabilize the entire economy.
American stocks suffered a bloodbath on Monday, with major stock indexes posting their biggest fall in more than 20 years.
The Dow Jones index fell by almost seven percent, a similar slump it had last recorded in 1987.
The index had already fallen before the vote, but no sooner was there any sign that the bill would not pass the House of Representatives than the index went into free fall.
Congress makes concession: US government can pump 700 billion dollars into the banks
Leaders of the US Congress and the administration of President George W. Bush have agreed on a broader form of financial assistance agreement for the US financial system.
It should be voted on early next week.
US lawmakers made a breakthrough in talks to pass a $700 billion (about 12 trillion kroner) bailout plan for the US financial system.
However, this does not mean victory.
Congressmen still have to negotiate some details of the agreement before they can publish and vote on the final version of the law.
The plan to support the financial system will be discussed in the US Congress on Monday.
Banking and Financial Services Committee Chairman Barney Frank told Reuters on Sunday.
According to various sources, the Senate could probably vote on the plan on Wednesday at the earliest.
According to economists, an announcement that the plan will be approved should be the first significant psychological factor for a recovery in financial markets.
After that, however, there was a &quot;disillusionment&quot; due to the complicated mechanisms of how to help the markets in practice.
Paulson: The plan has to be effective
&quot;We have made significant progress.
We have clarified our differing views on what a market stabilization package should look like,&quot; Democrat Nancy Pelosi told Bloomberg.
According to her, a final vote could be held on Sunday.
Representatives of the legislature met with the American Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson on Sunday night to give the government fund its final form.
This envisages a purchase of unsaleable mortgage assets from the finance companies, which plunges the finance companies into heavy losses and endangers the stability of the entire system.
&quot;We are on the verge of definitive agreement on a plan that will work and must be effective in the marketplace.
You have to continue with the recovery plan, but I think we&#39;re there,&quot; Paulson said.
A signal for Asian business
The global financial crisis is also clearly reflected in the stock markets, which are falling sharply.
According to Nevada Senator Harry Reid, lawmakers are trying to get a final agreement in Congress before Sunday.
This is intended to reassure investors about transactions in the Asian financial markets, which are in the first time zone where a decision by Congress could affect business on Monday.
So far, however, it is not entirely clear when both chambers of the American Congress will vote on the law, and it is also unclear whether the negotiations could fail at the last minute because of a problem.
Lawmakers hope it will pass in the next few days.
However, the law will still undergo some changes.
The total amount intended to help the system shall be divided into two parts.
The initial $350 billion should be made available as soon as possible, as President George Bush has demanded.
But Congress can block the distribution of the rest of the money if it feels the program isn&#39;t doing its job, with an additional $100 billion and later the final $350 billion.
Bush sees progress in negotiations as positive
While the President has veto power over this decision, Congress can override his veto.
Despite these changes, however, the core tenet of the program has remained, which was based on raising finance to buy bad mortgage securities that have fallen in value because hundreds of thousands of Americans are unable to pay off their mortgages.
&quot;We worked everything out.
The House of Representatives should be able to vote on the bill on Sunday and the Senate on Monday,&quot; said Republican Senator Judd Gregg.
US President Bush was also satisfied with the progress.
His spokesman Tony Fratto said Bush was pleased with Saturday&#39;s progress and &quot;appreciated the mutual effort to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy.&quot;
Restriction on golden parachutes
Senate Banking Committee Chairman Christopher Dodd, the lead negotiator, said lawmakers had agreed on accountability for the money program, protecting taxpayers from losses, concluding benefits and a timeline for funding the plan.
The new law also aims to limit the so-called golden parachutes for directors of companies involved in the scheme and establishes a committee to oversee the fund.
The Treasury should be in charge of this.
&quot;We&#39;ve worked very hard on this and made great strides towards an agreement that works and is important to the market and to all Americans,&quot; Paulson said.
The plan also envisages helping homeowners who are struggling to pay off their mortgage.
The government should negotiate new rates on mortgages it buys, with the aim of reducing borrowers&#39; monthly costs and allowing them to keep their homes.
Marek: Psychological help
The proposed plan is a good idea, according to Patria Finance chief economist David Marek, but implementation will be very difficult.
&quot;That&#39;s because you don&#39;t know by what mechanism and at what price the problematic assets will be bought.
This will be decisive for how the financial sector and the government share the losses between themselves,&quot; Marek told the iHNed.cz server this week.
Whether the plan is approved now or early next week is irrelevant in Marek&#39;s view.
&quot;It&#39;s much more important that congressmen agree to support the plan and that they pass it as soon as possible.
The psychological meaning of the agreement that there will be a farewell is the most important thing at this moment,&quot; stressed Marek.
Triumph of the right-wing populists in Austria, they come to a total of 29 percent
According to the first preliminary results, the early parliamentary elections on Sunday in Austria brought about a noticeable weakening of both parties in the previous grand coalition and a clear strengthening of the right-wing populist parties.
The Austrian People&#39;s Party (ÖVP) suffered particularly severe losses, where the position of the previous chairman, Wilhelm Molterer, is seriously in jeopardy.
In contrast, the electoral officer of the Alliance for the Future of Austria (BZÖ), Governor of Carinthia Jörg Haider, is gearing up for a triumphant return to federal politics.
According to the results so far, the Social Democracy (SPÖ) remains the strongest force in the country with 29.8 percent of the votes, but has lost 5.5 percent of the votes since the last elections in 2006.
The ÖVP did even worse, losing almost nine percent of the vote with 25.6 percent.
These are the worst results for these two major parties in Austria&#39;s post-war history, and especially for the People&#39;s Party, which had called for the early elections, this is a truly catastrophic result.
At the beginning of July, when the ÖVP left the coalition, the People&#39;s Party had a clear lead over the SPÖ.
But voters probably punished the party for letting the government fail.
Already in the first reactions to the results there was speculation about a possible resignation of the party chairman and former vice chancellor Wilhelm Molterer.
Observers believe that this could already be the case at an extraordinary meeting of the party executive on Monday.
Such a development would probably pave the way to the most likely way out of the election debacle, i.e. to a renewal of the grand coalition of SPÖ and ÖVP.
In view of the strengthening of both right-wing populist parties - the Freedom Party (FPÖ) received 18 percent, the BZÖ eleven percent of the votes - the Social Democrats expressed their fear that the year 1999 could repeat itself, when the People&#39;s Party made agreements with the populists (at that time it was the FPÖ still unified, in 2005 it split from the BZÖ) with regard to a joint government, which even resulted in sanctions from the European Union.
Jörg Haider is obviously counting on this development, who has already stated that he is prepared to work with any party and assumes that he will return to Vienna to take part in Austrian federal politics.
The Green Party also entered parliament, but suffered slight losses and slipped from third to fifth place among Austrian political parties.
No other party has probably cleared the four percent hurdle and consequently not entered parliament.
A knife-edge duel: MP3 players versus cell phones.
We will advise you on your choice
While almost every mobile phone can play MP3 files, no MP3 player can make calls.
So, of course, it looks like it&#39;s better to just buy a phone.
Despite everything, there are enough reasons why you should get a standalone player.
The choice depends entirely on the type of use and the requirements of the future owner.
Surely one hardly buys a great expensive record player for the home to listen to Maxim Turbulenc&#39;s latest album.
For one thing, such musical novelties don&#39;t appear on LPs, and from a qualitative point of view there&#39;s no objective reason for it either.
However, if you have art rock, jazz or blues LPs on your shelf, you are probably dreaming of at least one.
It&#39;s the same with music on trips, i.e. with compressed music, to put it simply - music in MP3 format.
There are also price and quality categories here.
For some it may not be acceptable to spend eight thousand crowns on a player, but a Pink Floyd fan will also find it difficult to cope with headphones for twenty crowns on the market.
Two extremes, between which there is enough space for everyone.
The selection is wide.
Battery life is also important.
Some good music players can do a lot more than just play music, but they can&#39;t even begin to do what cell phones can do.
No modern device can be used as universally as the telephone.
In addition to the primary functions, making phone calls and texting, it can play music and videos, record both, sometimes it has a better, sometimes a worse camera and it can perhaps also navigate.
And if you factor in the smartphones and communicators, you&#39;ve almost got a small computer in your pocket.
It&#39;s a small miracle, because no refrigerator can grill and no TV can take pictures.
But the universality of mobile phones also has disadvantages.
However, the more functions you use on your cell phone, the more frequently you will have to recharge it.
And playing music is one of the biggest energy guzzlers.
Few phones can play music for more than 10-12 hours, mostly much less.
In this regard, music players (especially the simplest ones) are significantly more powerful.
That&#39;s why you should expect the cheap cell phones to not be able to play music for more than a few hours.
If you still make phone calls from time to time, it&#39;s better to buy a charger for the office to be on the safe side - this also applies to more expensive devices.
You won&#39;t have this problem with MP3 players, even the lesser ones will last at least 9 hours of continuous use on a single charge.
Another problem arises when you want to transfer the music to your cell phone.
Unfortunately, only a small number of devices have a USB connection, and not every cell phone can be connected directly to a PC without special software.
Of course you can transfer the music directly to a storage medium, but only a few card readers can handle the tiny memory cards used in mobile phones without reduction.
With players, you do not need any special software, with a few exceptions (iPod).
You only need to feed the device with music from your PC via the USB port.
Most phones and players create their own music library, organized by artist name, album title, genre, or user rating, for example.
Some devices only map the tree structure of the address book, similar to Windows Explorer, some can do both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smart phones with OS).
Players are easier to use, cell phones can do more
When choosing a specific device, you should inquire about the battery life, storage capacity, quality and type of sound and, of course, ease of use.
If music is primarily a backdrop for you and you only listen to it briefly every day, for example on the tram, then any mobile phone that plays MP3 files will suffice.
What almost every mobile phone can do.
You don&#39;t have to particularly control which music formats a mobile phone or player can handle.
Everyone creates MP3, and most of the music you get will be in this format.
The format is one of the most widely used, and most devices can also play music in WMA format.
Less common is AAC (a format used by Apple and its iPods).
Better cell phones also make it possible to buy music online.
All you have to do is call up the corresponding pages of a provider (or another provider) via mobile Internet and you can already buy a song or album.
This service in and of itself can be a compelling argument as to why you should get a music phone.
Unfortunately, the provider&#39;s offer is poor and is mostly limited to fast radio hits.
The prices aren&#39;t the lowest either.
In general, however, it is assumed that this way of selling music (be it via GSM, Internet or wireless Internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people carry their cell phones with them.
When you feel like listening, reach for the phone in your pocket while the player is forgotten at home.
However, it depends on whether you always carry headphones or at least a wireless hands-free kit with you.
If not, you can fall back on the built-in speaker, which almost every mobile phone has, but only very few MP3 players.
For many, the biggest advantage of music cell phones will be the price.
The cheapest usually cost less than three thousand crowns.
You can get a decent Walkman for three or four thousand kronor.
The biggest handicap for most will be that there are no normal headphones.
The best and most sophisticated phones with a 3.5 mm opening for regular headphones cost up to fifteen thousand crowns.
The advantage of the player is that it is easy to use.
The simplest - and not necessarily the cheapest (see selection) - players can really use anyone.
A minimum of functions, the similarity in operation with the previously normal cassette recorder or, for example, the record player is obvious.
There is no threat of a collision in the form of an erroneously switched on mobile internet and a subsequent horrendous bill for data transmissions.
Which device should you use now?
Even the cheapest mobile phones (e.g. Vodafone 527) usually have a slot for exchangeable storage media (type M2, microSD, etc.).
Even if you buy a corresponding card later, two thousand crowns will suffice.
But be careful.
The basic models usually only support cards with a maximum capacity of 2 GB.
Only the most expensive can also read 8GB memory cards.
If you already own a mobile phone and still want to buy an inexpensive MP3 player, then reach for Cowon, Creativ, Sony, Samsung, Emgeton or iriver.
Depending on the capacity (max. 2 GB) you don&#39;t have to put more than 1100 crowns on the table.
If you belong to the more demanding listeners, it is better to use specialized mobile phones - walkmans (Sony Ericsson, some from Nokia and Samsung).
These devices have separate control buttons for MP3, and the ease of use is close to that of a single MP3 player.
The furthest along is Sony Ericsson, whose Walkman line of phones share the same user interface as MP3 players sold individually.
The same services in the same price category of up to four thousand crowns, but with a higher storage capacity (up to 16 GB) and a long battery life (typically 15 hours, maximum up to 35 hours) provide you with MP3 players from the above manufacturers .
The first virtual provider will come to the Czech Republic this year.
Perhaps
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite mature, the Czech providers offer practically all services as they are offered by their partners in Western Europe.
Nevertheless, something is missing here - a virtual provider that forces the classic ones to lower prices.
Perhaps this will not be long in coming.
We have often reported on Mobil.cz that the Czech mobile phone providers are among the most expensive in Europe.
This was also confirmed by the ČTÚ Telecommunications Authority, which pointed out that the price for an SMS here is higher than in the rest of the European Union.
After the latest steps taken by the European Commission in the field of regulation of roaming charges, a paradoxical situation is likely to arise - for some customers of Czech mobile operators, SMS from abroad will be cheaper than at home.
How come the prices in the Czech Republic are so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, it lacks the competition that really makes a declaration of war.
It may sound paradoxical, but in the Czech Republic there are three mobile networks and a penetration of well over 100%.
Mobile operators, on the other hand, like to complain that there is so much competition on the Czech market.
The Chairman of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Authority (ČTÚ) Pavel Dvořák, who has often said in the past that there is no room for another provider in the Czech Republic, often agrees with this.
It&#39;s probably true that a classic provider with its own network doesn&#39;t have many chances anymore (by the way, it would probably hardly find any frequencies either).
But there is one more option - a virtual provider.
The entry of virtual providers into the mobile phone market brought with it a significant price reduction, to which the classic mobile phone providers then had to react.
Even before such companies as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile entered the market in Great Britain, there were voices similar to those in the Czech Republic.
However, it has been shown that there is room for such providers and that they can be really successful.
By the way, you don&#39;t have to look far for examples.
In February this year we reported on the launch of the virtual provider Mobilking in Poland.
In just six months, this provider managed to attract more than 100 thousand customers, becoming the country&#39;s fifth largest provider.
Behind Mobilking is the Penta financial group, which owns U:fon in the Czech Republic, among others.
The advantage of virtual providers is that you can focus on a much more specific target group.
In order to be able to function effectively, virtual providers need far fewer customers than a classic provider.
You don&#39;t need relatively high costs for the construction, operation and maintenance of a mobile network.
In the world, virtual operators usually position themselves as low-cost companies - they offer cheap calls and SMS, but this is often accompanied by a less comprehensive range of services.
For example, Tesco Mobile in the UK offers SMS at least half the price of its competitors.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, going for a non-clichéd audience can also be a pretty good move.
This provider is aimed specifically at men.
&quot;Real guys choose Mobilking - the provider they like and can trust,&quot; said David Seibert, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, the company that operates this virtual provider.
It is difficult to say whether a concept similar to that in Poland could also gain a foothold in the Czech Republic.
The spokesman for Vodafone Miroslav Čepický also doubts this: &quot;The Czech market is relatively small for a market segment on which most virtual providers are based.
It&#39;s also relatively saturated from a service offering perspective.&quot;
No chance in the Czech Republic, say the mobile phone providers
However, it is almost certain that if a virtual mobile operator conquers the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
&quot;We are talking about an expansion of this successful project, but the negotiations in the Czech Republic do not look particularly promising.
Mobilking is more likely to enter the market in other countries in our region,&quot; said Jana Studničková, spokeswoman for the Penta financial group, in a telephone conversation for Mobil.cz.
Indirectly, she confirmed that the current mobile operators in the Czech Republic are not particularly inclined to this idea.
On the contrary, they try to do everything possible to ensure that no potential competitor arises.
The GTS Novera Group, which wants to take another step to become a real competitor of Telefónica O2 in the area of corporate customers, has been showing interest in launching a virtual mobile operator for a long time.
&quot;We have a keen interest in offering our customers not only fixed but also mobile telecommunications services.
And the sooner the better.
We have repeatedly negotiated this possibility with all Czech mobile operators.
We have already been able to make progress in negotiations with some of them,&quot; said Pavel Kaidl, spokesman for the group.
Maybe better times are coming now.
According to unofficial information, the first virtual provider can be expected perhaps by the end of the year.
So far, however, this has been surrounded by an insurmountable wall of silence.
&quot;At this moment we do not believe that there is room for a full-fledged virtual provider in the Czech Republic.
The Czech market has great specifics compared to other markets.
So far, no entity has approached us with a complex and serious project in this area,&quot; says Vlastimil Sršeň from the Telefónica O2 press department in his statement to Mobil.cz.
Other providers also point out the specifics of the Czech market.
T-Mobile spokeswoman Martina Kemrová, in rare agreement with O2&#39;s statement, adds: &quot;So far we haven&#39;t found a viable and mutually beneficial project to build on.&quot;
And she adds: &quot;Hardly any virtual provider will appear in the T-Mobile network by the end of the year.
At this point we should already have a concrete offer in order to be able to think on such short notice.&quot;
Vodafone is more focused on meeting its own 3G license requirements.
Miroslav Čepický says: &quot;We are open to negotiations with potential virtual providers, especially in the area of cost and infrastructure sharing.
This is exactly what we consider the best from the customer&#39;s point of view.
Vodafone&#39;s main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build a shared network for high-speed mobile Internet.&quot;
The responsible authorities - hand in hand with the providers
The actions of the cell phone providers are easy to understand, another provider would mean more competition, which would lead to falling prices and thus also to a drop in profits.
So why should you make it easier for such a competitor to enter the market?
The fact that the providers can pull together when something is at stake is also proven by the long back and forth about the creation of U:fon.
Probably the strongest pressure towards ČTÚ came from the company T-Mobile at the time when U:fon came onto the market.
This is also proven by the publicly available information from the ČTÚ websites.
Now, however, U:fon is a suitable argument as to why a virtual provider should not be allowed.
Martina Kemrová commented: &quot;The competitive environment of the mobile phone market has recently been strengthened by the market entry of a fourth mobile operator.
Considering the character of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is obvious that a new player would place high demands on the market itself and especially its services.&quot;
In view of this approach by the mobile phone providers, the absolute lack of interest on the part of the Czech regulatory authorities is surprising.
This is not just about the attitude of the ČTÚ, which unfortunately - in contrast to Great Britain and other highly developed countries - does not have the competence to intervene in economic competition in the Czech Republic.
This is owned exclusively by the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (ÚOHS).
This, however, related to this whole problem his very typical attitude.
&quot;The market entry of a virtual mobile phone provider would then be possible after a contract has been concluded between a mobile phone provider and a virtual provider for the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
So far, no such contract has been concluded, because the offer of potential interested parties was probably not sufficiently interesting for the classic providers,&quot; said Kristián Chalupa from the External Relations Department of the ÚOHS in response to our inquiry.
Such a formulation would not come as a surprise from representatives of the providers.
From an authority that represents consumer interests and, among other things, is supposed to ensure that nobody abuses their position on the market, this is more than questionable.
In particular, when Kristián Chalupa adds: &quot;Abroad, where virtual operators operate quite normally, it can be observed that their entry into the market has contributed to a price reduction of mobile telephone services.&quot;
However, pressure on the correct functioning of the market and price reduction are probably not in the interests of the ÚOHS.
What is really shocking about this case is the almost touching harmony of the three mobile phone providers that results from their reactions.
The question of whether it is really just a coincidence is obvious.
Just as the absolutely same petrol price at the gas stations is surely just a coincidence and the result of tough competition.
&quot;The Authority has not found any indication of any anti-competitive behavior in this matter and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the providers has a dominant market position, so they do not have the corresponding increased responsibility for their actions on the market.
The necessary tools for opening the mobile market to virtual providers are also likely to be lacking in the telecommunications regulator,&quot; Chalupa said in his statement.
The interpretation of market dominance is one of many contentious issues.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets, prepared by the ČTÚ, according to which telecommunications is a single market from the point of view of economic competition.
Of course, none of the Czech mobile operators has a dominant position in such a market.
However, some legal experts offer a different point of view - the approval of the network operator is always necessary for the market entry of a virtual provider.
And the mobile phone provider has - logically - the monopoly for his network.
This means that he necessarily has a dominant position in a certain segment.
Even if you don&#39;t go along with this line of argument, it should at least be a warning for the ÚOHS that three mobile phone providers are proceeding in a remarkably similar way.
Complaints from a number of interested parties (including the aforementioned company GTS Novera) show that they encounter very similar obstacles when negotiating with all providers.
Shifting the responsibility onto the ČTÚ is a fairly common trick in telecommunications services, with which the ÚOHS distances itself from the whole matter.
This has already been observed in a number of similar cases.
Unfortunately, it was not possible to extend the competences of the ČTÚ to the area of economic competition in telecommunications in the recently adopted amendment to the Telecommunications Act, although a number of experts hoped that this would improve the situation.
The representatives of the ÚOHS must know this all too well, but they probably have other interests.
It works when no one is looking
First of all, the functioning of any pseudo-virtual providers, of which there are several in the Czech mobile networks, remains unnoticed.
These are companies that issue their own price lists for mobile telecommunications services, but only some of them are public.
Normally, these are companies that operate in the field of multilevel marketing.
For example, Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and others offer their own mobile phone services.
The price lists of these companies usually only reach a select few.
The joke of the matter is that the company appears to the operator as a classic corporate customer who orders a large number of SIM cards.
As an important customer, they will then receive special price offers (and other offers).
The problem is that the terms and conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit similar types of resale.
&quot;If there are cases that you describe, then it may be a matter of breach of contractual terms, which we will then deal with, which may lead to termination of cooperation with the relevant company,&quot; Martina Kemrová replied to our question to this problem.
However, it is quite unlikely that word of this will not get around to those responsible at the mobile phone provider.
Especially in the case of the three companies mentioned, there can be thousands of customers.
However, no operator opposes such an approach.
From the activities of these companies, they generate not inconsiderable profits, at the same time - in contrast to the actual virtual providers - they are not affected by the actual official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický draws attention to possible problems: &quot;The law allows for such types of speculation, despite everything, the services of these companies are only used by a very small percentage of customers.
They also have to accept that the SIM card in their phone is not in their name, so they cannot fully dispose of it like the normal customers of the mobile network providers.&quot;
But that alone should at least seem strange to the ČTÚ.
Another question also arises for the ÚOHS.
If cell phone providers turn a blind eye to such an approach, why are they blocking themselves against a virtual provider?
It should be added that the ÚOHS has quite strong powers to detect such activities, and if it doesn&#39;t want to, it doesn&#39;t have to be satisfied with providers&#39; declarations that they don&#39;t know about it and that their terms and conditions forbid it.
When the Czech Republic is no longer the most expensive
As has already been emphasized several times in the text, the market entry of virtual providers brought with it a significant drop in prices for the various services.
In practically all countries where virtual providers have emerged, the classic providers have tried to prevent their emergence to a greater or lesser extent.
The arguments they used were practically identical - too small or too saturated a market, problems with the quality of services, etc.
In the highly developed countries, however, it was precisely at these moments that the regulatory bodies intervened, who were not trying to protect the interests of the mobile phone providers, but rather those of their customers.
Whether through formal action or non-formal pressure, they managed to create the first virtual operator, and others followed.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulators are throwing the whole case at each other like a hot potato.
Based on our experience, we cannot get rid of the impression that lack of clarity in the competences is more than favorable in these cases.
But let&#39;s not throw in the towel.
If the background information is correct and a virtual provider appears soon, the Czech mobile communications market may soon start moving again.
If a provider allows the creation of a virtual mobile network provider, the ÚOHS will not remain inactive when it comes to rejecting (discriminating against) other interested parties.
And the Czechs will finally no longer be making more expensive calls than the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Pick the best
Listen to the four versions of the new Czech national anthem.
Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek presented the new recordings of the national anthem Where is my homeland at a ceremony on Sunday to mark the Day of Czech Statehood.
The anthem was newly recorded by the National Theater Orchestra conducted by Jiří Bělohlávek.
Four versions are available - with male or female solo vocals, in a choral version and in an instrumental version.
The vocal version was taken over by Kateřina Kněžínková and Adam Plachetka.
The arrangers of the anthem versions are Otakar Jeremiáš and Jaroslav Krček.
You can listen to all four versions at once on the iHNed.cz server.
For Bělohlávek, the Czech national song is one of the most beautiful anthems.
He had previously told Czech Radio that he had chosen singers with young, representative voices who were distinctive and popular for the solo versions.
&quot;Right from the start I tried to keep a clear diction with both and then also with the choir, so that the text can be understood well, so that there is harmony,&quot; says the conductor.
The Czech national anthem will celebrate its 175th anniversary next year.
The song Kde domov můj was first heard in 1834 on the stage of the Estates Theater in the originally Czech play Fidlovačka by Josef Kajetán Tyl, the music was by František Škroup.
It became popular and people spontaneously embraced it.
The first verse of the song then became an organic part of the national anthem after the formation of Czechoslovakia in 1918.
It remained one of the seven state symbols even after the formation of the independent Czech Republic.
