On Wednesday, the Prague public transport company will also be using a chip for the first time
Wednesday, October 1, 2008 will go down in the history of Prague transport as the date when the first passengers to board a metro, tram or bus carried an electronic coupon in their pocket instead of a paper ticket.
Around one hundred thousand people who have the Opencard chip card can currently buy this.
Passengers can buy a 30-day, 90-day or annual coupon (valid from January 1, 2009) and have it loaded onto their chip card at the same time in the information centers and branches of the public transport companies on the subway - Muzeum, Můstek, Nádraží Holešovice, Anděl, Roztyly, Letňany, Kobylisy, Rajská zahrada, Kačerov and Luka stations.
Since yesterday, the coupons have also been available online on the transport company&#39;s website www.dpp.cz.
The service was used by more than four hundred customers well into the afternoon.
Those who use internet sales can really forget about the issue window in the subway stations, where previously they regularly had to wait in long lines for their paper tickets.
You buy the coupon over the Internet, which is loaded onto the open card in one of the thirteen branches of the city library.
&quot;At these points, there is also a counter with trained staff available to travelers who advise those interested in buying online and also put the coupon on the card,&quot; says project spokesman Martin Opatrný.
In addition to the libraries, you can also load the electronic coupons onto the Opencard at self-service machines that are installed in some underground vestibules.
What do these machines look like?
They are red, reminiscent of ticket validators, and passengers may have noticed them in Roztyly, Budějovická, IP Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská metro stations.
&quot;Currently there are five of them in the city, but by the end of the year there should be eighty,&quot; adds Opatrný.
An automatic machine checks the coupon instead of the driver
Operating the vending machines, which will work from tomorrow, is simple.
All you have to do is insert the chip card and the previously purchased coupon will appear automatically.
Starting tomorrow, the electronic coupons will be valid not only in the capital, but also in the surrounding area.
That is, on suburban trains and on bus lines Nos. 300 to 499, which are used mainly by residents of the Central Bohemian Region to get to the capital.
&quot;In the trains that belong to Prague&#39;s integrated transport, the conductors have readers with which they can check the validity of the coupons by time and zone,&quot; explains Filip Drápal from the Ropid organization responsible for ticket inspection. This organization compiles the timetables for the Prague public transport company.
The suburban buses have card readers at the cash register next to the driver.
When boarding, the chip card not only has to be shown to the driver, but the Opencard has to be placed in a marked place on the side of the cash register.
This allows the driver to check the validity of the coupons that have been loaded.
&quot;If a passenger wants to check the validity of the coupons that have been played, nothing is easier than asking the driver for this information,&quot; says Drápal.
A passenger who does not ride suburban buses and does not know when the coupon expires can, in turn, go to the self-service machines where the coupons are loaded onto the card.
Here the information on the validity of his documents is shown on the display of the device.
The Sudetes demanded a referendum from the USA
In 1945, the Sudeten Germans requested that the Bohemian Forest be annexed to the United States.
This comes from a letter stored in the collections of the South Bohemian Scientific Library.
If we can&#39;t be part of Germany or Austria, at least we want to live under the auspices of the United States of America.
In 1945, some groups of Sudeten Germans are said to have approached the US President with such a wish.
This is evident, among other things, from a letter that has been preserved in a private archive and is now kept in the collections of the South Bohemian Scientific Library.
In the letter, the Germans from Krumau asked the American President not to allow the return of the &quot;Sudetengau&quot; - which was occupied by Hitler on the basis of the Munich Agreement - to Czechoslovakia.
&quot;We understood the situation correctly and really want to be sure of the words that the American units are not entering German territory as oppressors and enemies, but as liberators,&quot; says a letter, which began with the words &quot;People to whom fate dear to the heart of the Sudetes&quot;.
Since the connection to Czechoslovakia leads the Sudeten Germans to assume - knowing the Czech national character - that they would expect brutality, ruthlessness, incomprehension, oppression and slavery, the authors of the letter ask the American President to take over the protectorate of the to take over the Bohemian Forest.
&quot;We cannot believe that, regardless of the views of a quarter of a million inhabitants, you are giving this area to a foreign state that oppresses and tries to eliminate minorities and did absolutely nothing to the Allied victory,&quot; the letter reads .
The reason why the authors cannot sign is allegedly fear of revenge from the &quot;Czech oppressors&quot;.
If the US President has any doubts about the attitude of the Bohemian Forest Germans, it would be sufficient if he would initiate a referendum in the Bohemian Forest Gau about whether the residents wanted to become part of the USA or live under the auspices of the United States.
Although the text of the letter may sound somewhat naïve in today&#39;s knowledge of post-war history, according to some contemporary witnesses it paints a good picture of the expectations of the Sudeten Germans at the time.
Even if the Bohemian Germans had to at least suspect that their deportation from the republic would be negotiated, only a few of them even acknowledged such a possibility.
Some waited for the United States and Britain to negotiate some form of autonomy for the Sudetes.
Still others thought they could just stay in Czechoslovakia.
This is also confirmed by the famous Austrian journalist Gustav Chalupa, who comes from Budweis.
During the war he served as a Budweiser German in the Navy on the Baltic Sea.
When he was taken prisoner by the British at the end of the war and taken to a POW camp in Holstein, dozens of other Bohemian Germans came to him to teach them Czech.
&quot;They thought that when they came home, Czech would suit them,&quot; says Chalupa.
In his opinion, none of the German prisoners of war who lived in Czechoslovakia before the war expected that they would be expelled from the republic on the basis of the Beneš decrees.
