Questions after the accident: Are stewards on the bus illegal?
The law does not know them, walking around in a long-distance coach is not allowed
In connection with the tragic accident involving a Student Agency bus near Padua, Italy, the question has been raised as to whether stewards and passengers are allowed to walk back and forth on the bus while it is being driven.
&quot;If we wanted to strictly and formally comply with the law, then the activity of a steward is contrary to the law on road traffic,&quot; said spokesman for the Ministry of Transport Karel Hanzelka.
The accident that killed a 22-year-old stewardess last week was likely caused by the driver of the truck crossing the path of the bus.
To make matters worse, the young woman was sitting next to the driver at that moment, in the least secure seat in the car, although she still had two other seats available.
However, a bus can also have an accident or brake sharply at the moment when the steward is delivering coffee or newspapers.
It also plays a role whether the bus is equipped with standing room according to the vehicle registration document.
If this is not provided for on the bus, the travelers must be seated.
Student Agency long-distance coaches are not standing room; which the director of the company, Radim Jančura, confirmed to Aktuálně.cz.
&quot;We discussed this with the Ministry and this did not agree to the movement of travelers at first.
This was later withdrawn and we came to a consensus that passengers should be allowed to go to the toilet during the journey if they have their seat,&quot; he shared his point of view.
The law knows no steward
&quot;There is no clear legal interpretation of the role of a steward - no legislation describes that role.
However, there is also no legislation prohibiting the carrier from providing services.
The law on road traffic only recognizes the term vehicle attendant; However, it does not define their rights and obligations,&quot; adds the spokesman for the ministry Hanzelka clearly.
On the other hand, the Director of the Road Vehicles Department of the Ministry of Transport, Josef Pokorný, believes that the law covers this issue retrospectively.
&quot;It depends on whether the bus also has standing room in the product approval.
That&#39;s all,&quot; he emphasizes.
Buses are divided into city buses, where there is standing room and the maximum speed is restricted, local standing room buses with a higher speed limit, and long-distance non-standing room buses with the maximum speed limit and seats equipped with seat belts.
Like on an airplane, says the expert
BESIP road safety specialist Jaroslav Hořín does not see any fundamental problem in the movement of stewards on board a bus.
&quot;If you drive smoothly, there are not many dangers; the situation is comparable to service on board an airplane.
Again, it&#39;s not certain when turbulence will come and the stewardess may hit her head.&quot;
&quot;However, if a bus brakes sharply, then of course the laws of physics also apply.
Just like in a city bus or in a tram.
The carrier must clarify the safety of the stewards through internal regulations,&quot; he says, adding that the law does not fully resolve this issue.
Jančura is ready to cancel the services
Student Agency is the only bus company to offer steward services.
The company employs around two hundred people in this capacity.
Even after the accident, the director does not see her job as risky.
&quot;But as soon as I get the impression that the steward&#39;s job is risky, I&#39;ll drop it.
Coffee and newspapers can be given to travelers upon boarding.
It would also reduce costs,&quot; he says.
The director of Asiana Alexej Litvin explains the lack of stewards on his buses as an interest in safety. However, his company operates only a fraction of lines compared to Student Agency.
&quot;We don&#39;t have any stewardesses, but we&#39;ve been against that from the start.
Sooner or later this will end in some fatal accident,&quot; he told Týden.cz less than a year ago.
That was an unbelievable tragedy
A young stewardess from the Pilsen region, who had worked for the company for two years, was killed in an accident on a bus to Naples.
The Slovenian truck probably turned off the hard shoulder without indicating and blocked the bus&#39;s route.
The driver of the bus tried to avoid it by making a sharp maneuver, but collided with the truck with his right front part.
Jančura denies that the two seats for the stewards were sold.
&quot;These seats cannot be reserved for long-distance connections, they are blocked.&quot;
Company plans to sue truck driver
With compensation for the young woman&#39;s family, the agency will not wait for the court verdict, but it also expects financial compensation from the culprit.
A law change?
Not in sight
More precise regulation of the movement of stewards on board a bus could bring a legal regulation on which a thirty-strong team of experts from the Ministry of Transport has been working for more than a year.
&quot;However, no concrete conclusion has yet been reached.
Buses are not necessarily on the agenda either, rather the point system, the maximum speed on the motorway and the use of mobile phones when driving,&quot; says the expert Hořín.
&quot;The Ministry of Transport does not consider the work of the stewards to be something that could significantly endanger the safety of passengers,&quot; said Hanzelka, although monitoring the safety of the buses is the responsibility of the police and health and safety authorities.
A Czech judges the struggle for the bottom of the sea
He approaches an electronic map showing Australia and the adjacent sea areas.
However, he is not interested in the continent, but in a small point lost in the blue of the ocean.
&quot;The island is part of Australia and along with it the adjacent seabed.
The area is as big as the continent itself,&quot; says Italian lawyer Luigi Santosuosso, who is part of the thirty-strong team at the UN Division for Oceans and the Law of the Sea.
His boss, the division director, the Czech lawyer Václav Mikulka, follows the interpretation and adds to it from time to time.
There is a spirit of work and enthusiasm here.
The seabed holds a little-known world that is rich in natural springs.
Crude oil can be found here, as well as ore and other non-renewable raw materials, but also previously unknown living organisms that, for example, carry the key to the development of a drug against cancer.
A seabed larger than the mainland
The riparian states vehemently announced their claim to the new sea areas today.
According to a UN convention, they make use of their rights, which they agreed on in 1982 in Montego Bay, Jamaica.
This is primarily the area of the so-called continental shelf, which often extends several hundred kilometers from the shore of a country into the sea.
According to the Convention, this country has an exclusive claim to all sources of the continental shelf.
&quot;Put simply, the continental shelf is considered that part of the sea floor and its floor that is a natural continuation of the continent below the sea surface.
It crosses the borders of the coastal sea, often also the limit of two hundred nautical miles of the so-called exclusive economic zone,&quot; explains Mikulka.
The application that the country in question submits to the Commission for the Determination of the External Boundaries of the Continental Shelf must be backed up by extensive scientific and technical documentation, which is based on many costly investigations and measurements.
It is the result of many years of preparatory work.
&quot;One of our tasks is to provide legal and technical support to the Commission.
The Commission has so far considered five applications from Russia, Brazil, Australia, Ireland and New Zealand.
So far, only the latter three countries have succeeded,&quot; Mikulka adds.
The success of Australia, which was the first country to significantly expand its sea areas, recently met with an international echo.
But New Zealand is also a winner - the seabed expanse the country was given last week by the commission is about 1.6 million square kilometers, about six times the size of the state proper.
Both countries have invested millions of dollars in the investigations.
They promise that the future profit they will derive from the use of the seabed will be of inestimable value.
Other states will also gradually submit their applications.
They can do so for ten years from the moment they ratify the &quot;Montego Bay Accords&quot;.
Where the continental shelf ends, the area of the ocean floor designated by the Convention as &quot;the common heritage of mankind&quot; begins.
No state will then have a special position here.
The right to promote in this area is granted by an international institution set up by the Convention.
&quot;But the seabed is not gold mining country,&quot; says Director Mikulka, exaggerating somewhat, adding that its &quot;individual areas are precisely defined by law and the system is contractually anchored.&quot;
Czechs in the Pacific
Part of the seabed now also belongs to the Czech Republic.
It shares it with other states of the former Eastern Bloc within the framework of the joint organization &quot;Interoceanmetal&quot;.
In 1991, as a result of the convention, it received the status of a so-called &quot;pioneering investor&quot;, as did the investors in a few other countries.
The organization has the right to mine in the ClarionClipperton zone in the Pacific Ocean between Mexico, Hawaii and Kiribati.
The area to be explored by the investor is slightly larger than the former Czechoslovakia.
The seabed is indented there, it is a kind of Tatras on the seabed.
&quot;You can mine there on a total area of 75,000 square kilometers.
The area is a rich site of polymetallic concretions containing nickel, copper, cobalt and manganese,&quot; said another jurist, Indian Pakshi Rajan.
