`Auto Bee&#39; that avoids collisions
In order to advance the development of technologies for accident prevention, this time Nissan took inspiration from nature, more precisely from bees.
The Japanese company has developed a robot whose flight is based on the swarming behavior of bees and avoids accidents.
This robot is a Bio-mimetic Car Robot Drive or BR23C and represents the first step in technologies for accident prevention.
The engineers from the technical development center of Nissan Motor Co. have developed this small robot in cooperation with the Research Center for Advanced Science and Technology of the renowned University of Tokyo (Japan).
According to Kazuhiro Doi, Head of Technology PR and R&amp;D Brand Management, the BR23C represents an extension of Nissan&#39;s four-layer security shield.
This robot aims to ensure that the cars of this brand are able to avoid the collisions.
During flight, each bee creates its own oval-shaped flight space, very similar to the Nissan Security Shield.
Most importantly, the bee&#39;s compound eyes can see in all directions over an angle of 300 degrees, allowing it to fly uninterrupted in its personal airspace.
In order to reproduce the all-round perspective, the technicians developed what is known as the Laser Range Finder (LRF).
It detects obstacles up to two meters in front of the BR23C and within a 180-degree radius, calculates the distance to the object and sends a signal to an on-board microprocessor, which is immediately translated into a collision avoidance signal
`The moment when obstacle is detected, the little robot will imitate the bee flight and immediately change direction by rotating its wheels by 90º or more angle to avoid the collision.
The biggest difference to any other system is that this evasive maneuver is completely instinctive.
If it weren&#39;t, the robot might not be able to react with enough speed to avoid obstacles,&#39; explains Toshiyuki Andoh, the director of the Mobility Laboratory and the lead engineer on this project.
In contrast to a bee, the robot cannot deviate up or down, but also not across corners; he can only move in two dimensions and in the direction that allows him to turn his wheels and not in the infinite directions and in infinite ways as the bees do.
For this reason, in addition to acceleration and deceleration functions, Nissan has used the rotation function to make the little robot avoid collisions.
`This device only takes a few seconds to process the information and act on it.
It does not require storing neither information nor intuitive logic of the performed maneuvers, so it can work continuously with only a few tens of KB of disk space.
That sounds surprising, but it&#39;s not about the GBs and not even the MBs of storage space.
This is the first step in the development of instant collision prevention technologies, a technology that Nissan predicts will bring to production cars in the next decade.
The robot uses lithium polymer batteries, which are lighter and last longer than a variety of lithium ion batteries.
Another possible application of this technology in the future could be the integration of the unit with a GPS satellite navigation system to guide driving to the destination avoiding the obstacles on the way.
