The national blood pools managed by the Canadian Red Cross Blood Donation Service are known to have been contaminated with HIV and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
Faced with this drama and public dissatisfaction, in February 1994 the Government of Canada, led by Judge Horace Krever, launched a public inquiry aimed at shedding light on the circumstances leading up to such a tragedy and formulating policy to prevent another catastrophe of this kind.
At the time, while Judge Krever was reluctant to deliver his report, several provinces set up a committee to develop a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Committee Gélineau fulfilled this mandate.
According to Gélineau and Krever&#39;s reports, two blood banks were established in Canada: Hema-Quebec, serving Quebec, and the Canadian Blood Society, to service the other provinces and the two territories.
`In 1998, when Hema-Quebec started its work, barely 38% of the people had confidence in the blood bank system in Quebec, recalls Dr. Decary.
The situation was discouraging.
Through the tremendous effort to improve blood safety and work in this area over the following years, we have regained the public&#39;s trust,&#39; she says, before proudly pointing out that as of early 2008, nearly 94% of Quebec&#39;s population is now had faith in Hema-Quebec.
dr However, Décary keeps in mind that &#39;trust is something extremely fragile&#39;.
Since its inception on September 28, 1998, Hema-Quebec has operated on a prudent basis.
At that time we were witnessing the emergence in Europe of numerous cases of the human form of mad cow disease, a new type of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, says this woman, who has been at the helm since its inception in 1998.
`And we didn&#39;t have the slightest idea if this disease could be transmitted through the blood.
So we invoked one of the main guidelines of the Krever and Gélineau reports, which is that when you don&#39;t know and when a disease is progressing slowly, as is evidently the case with Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, you use exclusionary measures manifested by degeneration of the brain, which inevitably leads to death.
So in April 1999 blood was not accepted from anyone who had been in the UK for more than a month since 1980.
Well, several years ago it was proved beyond any doubt that this disease is transmitted through the blood.
So this event showed us that the principle of prudence that we applied makes sense.
In 1999, a much more accurate technique for detecting HIV appeared on the market: the nucleic acid tests (NST), which make it possible to detect the presence of the virus itself directly in the donor&#39;s blood, and not that of antibodies to the virus, as is the case with was the case with the previously used tests.
The NST made it possible to shorten the incubation period that occurs between the moment the person is infected and when the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, explains the specialist.
This time was reduced to less than a week.
This significantly reduced the risk that certain donors could be infected without knowing it and not being able to detect it.
These improvements made it possible to significantly reduce the risk of transmitting AIDS through a blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people is at risk of receiving HIV-infected blood.
`In other words, it would take 12 million units of blood to be distributed before anyone would be infected with HIV.
Since Hema-Quebec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 units of blood each year, it would be more than 24 years before a case of HIV being transmitted via a unit of blood would occur.
I believe that nowadays one can feel comfortable receiving or prescribing a blood transfusion to restore health,&#39; said the Hema-Quebec executive director.
`Our challenge for the next ten years is to keep our products safe.
You never know what pathogens may enter the system.
The Chikungunya virus, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted by insects via the blood, appeared on the island of Réunion only last year.
We have to monitor continuously,&#39; continues Dr. Décary before emphasizing that in addition to secure supplies, Hema-Quebec must also provide adequate supplies.
`Demand is increasing because the population is aging.
Because cancer-fighting treatments are more aggressive, patients often need new red blood cells or platelets.
The aging of the population is also affecting the blood donor network, which comprises on average only 3% of Quebecers who are eligible to donate blood. &#39;
Any healthy person aged 18 or older who meets the eligibility criteria can donate blood every 56 days, i.e. six times a year.
