What was produced in the invoice factory of Zuschlag &amp; Co.?
On October 8th, negotiations begin in the criminal trial against János Zuschlag and his accomplices.
The accused are accused in particular of participation in organized crime, as well as grossly negligent damage and business fraud, and other criminal acts - including document forgery.
According to the public prosecutor, the funds raised from the tenders were used for their own purposes, while the services provided were often documented with forged invoices.
State funds and subsidies from the self-government - a total of HUF 65 million - are said to have flowed partly into the coffers of the organization Fiatal Baloldal, partly into the private coffers of individuals.
As the investigating authorities announced, fictitious invoices were presented when the tender funds were obtained, and the clubs are said to have failed to fulfill their obligations.
According to the indictment, a large part of the invoices are said to have been forged.
The blocks of accounts were bought at the Józsefváros market, the round seals were made in Kiskunhalas.
The decision on which companies to issue the invoices to was made on the round trip north of Lake Balaton, on which István Lados was sent by János Zuschlag.
In the course of this &quot;exploration tour&quot; Lados should find guesthouses and restaurants.
He demanded bills for consumption so that he could later issue bills for the Ministry of Youth and Sports, the Ministry of Social Affairs and Labor and the Budapest self-government based on these templates.
Most of these accounts are said to have been manipulated by István Lados and his accomplice, András Őri, with the latter, according to our information, being responsible for drafting the relevant reports.
One of the destinations of Lados&#39; &quot;discovery tour&quot; was a beer pub.
As can be seen from two invoices issued by Zuschlag and Co in 2003, the catering business is said to have catered to the group of ninety from the Biztos Pont Egyesület association.
But now the head of the company states that such a large group would not have fit into the restaurant all at once.
Another invoice issued in the summer of 2002 to the Jobb Jövőért Foundation, later known as Együtt a Harmadik Évezredért, also had serious form and content errors.
In a guesthouse in Badacsonytomaj, which only has three rooms and cannot accommodate more than ten people at a time, 130 guests are said to have stayed, according to the bill.
