Meals were also stated on the bill, although the restaurant had not been in operation for a long time.
The industrious bill forgers also failed to verify that the Budapest travel agency they targeted only offers trips abroad, so they included Hungary trips on the cash bill, which also contradicted the company&#39;s accounting practice.
As became known in the course of the investigation, they also included VAT on the invoices, although travel agency services related to a country outside the EU are exempt from VAT.
The amount of VAT was incorrect on four invoices issued by Hotel Révfülöp Kft. to the Jobb Jövőért Foundation, as the company only charges 15 percent VAT instead of 25 percent. In addition, the employees only issue machine invoices, but the forged documents were handwritten .
Another mistake the &quot;accountants&quot; made was that in one case they stated &quot;transport of goods&quot; as the service provided, although this is not offered by the company specializing in investment advice, the prosecutor said.
Further formal errors - wrong invoice format, wrong stamp - was to be owed that to Együtt a Harmadik Évezredért Alapítvány, as well as to XXI. Századi Kulturális Egyesület and Biztos Pont could be exposed as forgeries.
