The psychology of overbidding - or why we are willing to pay more
At auction, buyers tend to spend more and overvalue what&#39;s on offer.
Neurologists and economists at the University of New York have now succeeded in discovering the neurological-economic basis of this well-known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to a study published in &quot;Science&quot; magazine, people do not want to be defeated in a competition such as an auction on eBay and are therefore willing to even pay excessive prices.
Researchers tried to explore the neurological scheme of this &quot;game&quot; using experimental auctions.
One group of the volunteers was asked to play the lottery while the other took part in a playful activity - in both cases the active brain regions of the subjects were examined using functional magnetic resonance (fMRI).
In both games, the participants could win money, but increased activity of the striatum, a complex below the cerebral cortex, was measured in the losers of the auction, in which overbidding the opponent plays an important role.
Among many other functions, this brain region is responsible for the &quot;self-reward&quot; of the nervous system.
The researchers therefore suggested that the price increase could be explained by avoiding an overreaction of the striatum.
In order to substantiate their thesis, the economists in the research group also carried out investigations into the tracking of money.
In this case, three groups should bid against one partner under different conditions.
The control group was told the true value of the product, after which they made their bets.
Another group was also promised a $15 reward if they emerged victorious from the game.
The third group received $15 before the auction, which was also lost in case of a lost game.
The only difference between the two groups was that one emphasized winning while the other emphasized losing.
In support of the neurologists&#39; hypothesis, however, members of the &quot;against-losing&quot; group were willing to bet higher than those in the control and &quot;win&quot; groups, respectively.
&quot;These results cannot be derived from any previous economic theory.
So far, they have only justified the behavior observed at auctions with the joy of winning or the avoidance of risk.
The contradiction between these two theories has been resolved thanks to neuroimaging techniques, so we now have a third explanation ready&quot; - said Andrew Schotter, professor at the School of Economics at New York University.
Hepatitis: when to see a doctor
Around half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary this chronic liver disease is listed among the leading causes of death.
The number of people infected in this country is estimated at 100,000, but only 7,000 are treated, which is because the patients often do not know that they are infected.
Hepatitis is the collective term for infectious liver diseases caused by various viruses.
Symptoms are often similar - hepatitis and jaundice are common, but the causative agents and the diseases are different.
Depending on the pathogen, the hepatitis viruses are spread in two different ways: in hepatitis A and E through the digestive tract (for example through contaminated food or water), in hepatitis B, C and D the viruses can be spread through blood and other body fluids (such as semen, vaginal secretions or saliva).
In any case, travelers are recommended to be vaccinated against viruses A and B; there is no vaccine against virus C.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear about two to three weeks after eating the contaminated food and are generally accompanied by discomfort, weakness, abdominal pain and nausea.
After that, jaundice appears on the skin and eyes, the stools become light-colored, the urine dark, and recovery can take up to two to three weeks.
Around the world, around 1 million people die every year from the far more serious diseases caused by hepatitis B, such as liver cancer and liver cirrhosis.
The main reason for this is that, according to estimates, only every tenth infected person is on medication.
Hepatitis C can also have serious consequences: if left untreated, it can lead to liver cirrhosis and liver cancer.
Most infected people do not even know about their disease, since the pathogen insidiously destroys the liver cells - in many cases the first symptoms appear after 20-30 years.
Timely prevention, such as regular check-ups, is therefore essential.
There are three groups in which this condition is more common: those who had a blood transfusion before 1991, drug users, and those with tattoos.
The number of people suffering from chronic hepatitis C worldwide is currently estimated at 200 million.
Since the disease can already be detected in a routine laboratory test, it is advisable to consult your family doctor at the first sign of unknown origin.
If recognized in time, the disease can be cured, the virus can be eradicated, which eliminates the risk of infection and prevents the development of cancer.
September 30 is World Hepatitis Day, organized for the first time in 2004 by patient advocacy groups worldwide.
The aim of the campaign is to raise awareness of this chronic hepatitis caused by viruses, how it develops and the importance of early detection.
