Intelligent car imitates the flight of the bumblebee
What would be the best way to develop new technologies to avoid accidents if not to imitate obstacle sensors found in nature?
For example that of the bees.
An amazing project was unveiled at CEATEC in Japan, in which Nissan engineers were inspired by bumblebees to create new crash-avoidance systems.
In collaboration with Tokyo University, Nissan has built the BR23C auto-robot-controlled biomimetic system, a mini-car endowed with the properties of bees, with the aim of supporting the development of a system that avoids all collisions.
In flight, each bee forms its own oval &quot;private space,&quot; which is very similar to our own &quot;shield,&quot; said Kazuhhiro Doi, product manager for technology PR and research development, at the show.
The bee&#39;s compound eye, which can see in any direction and at an angle of over 300 degrees, plays an important role in this.
To mimic the function of the compound eye, the researchers took up the idea of the laser-guided distance meter.
This identifies obstacles in front of the BR23C in a 180 degree field of view within 2 meters, calculates their distances and sends signals to the onboard microprocessor which immediately initiates the collision avoidance process.
The obstacle is registered in a split second, and the car robot immediately changes course, similar to the movement of bees, by rotating the tires by the appropriate angle.
In contrast to previous systems, this maneuver takes place purely instinctively.
&quot;If it weren&#39;t so, the auto-robot wouldn&#39;t be able to react fast enough to avoid the obstacles,&quot; said Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the &quot;Mobility Laboratory&quot; and the auto-robot project.
The system must react instinctively and immediately, as this technology corresponds to the innermost and most vulnerable part of the protective shield - a layer within which accidents are currently considered unavoidable.
The whole process must reflect the behavior of the bees when avoiding other bees.
And it has to happen in a split second.
However, in contrast to the bees, the evasion cannot be up, down, or even diagonally - it can only be two-dimensional, and only in the direction of the turning ability of the tires.
While the bees have an infinite number of options here to avoid other bees, the researchers were only able to use the rotary motion, or acceleration and deceleration, of the autorobot.
