Fox in the chicken coop
Life and health insurance companies in America often refuse to contract with a customer because of a person&#39;s drug use.
Data protection experts fear that the data market could become uncontrollable.
&quot;There are data protection programs that always link the use of drug data to the consent of the person concerned.
These should be in independent hands, otherwise we&#39;ll entrust the chickens to the fox,&quot; the Washington Post quoted Richard Dick, developer of the prescription tracking program.
Insurance companies set the fees and the amounts paid out in the event of damage depending on the state of health of the customer, and if the risk is overestimated, the insurance will not be taken out in the first place.
In the past, the customer was sent for a medical examination, and the contract was concluded only in the knowledge of the results of the examination.
Ten years ago, Dick invented a much cheaper method: Using the customer&#39;s identification number, he gets the data from the pharmacies for the last year and a half, i.e. which preparations were bought, and the program uses this to calculate which illness the customer is suffering from and what his state of health is is.
For example, if he regularly buys large quantities of cholesterol-lowering drugs, the inference would be that his blood lipid levels are intractably high, which would automatically put him in a higher risk group.
There are several versions of the program in circulation - some even define a risk multiplier so that insurance companies only have to do the paperwork, although there are minor difficulties.
One of the disadvantages is that many medications can be taken for different purposes, such as for migraines and hot flashes, but also for depression.
From the insurers&#39; point of view, the latter is a high-risk factor, while the former are not.
Special companies have been set up to query and process the data, which ask the patient for their consent before obtaining the data.
They are now required to do so by law, although omissions have so far not been punished.
Some companies even process the results of laboratory tests and combine them with data on drug use. They thus provide an even more precise picture of the patient&#39;s state of health.
More and more companies have access to the data, and at the same time controlling its use is becoming more difficult.
Although there is a separate data protection law for health data, its effect only extends to service providers in the health sector and insurance companies.
The draft law has already been submitted to Congress, according to which the authorities could also control the data processing companies.
Dick Richard recognizes that this is not enough, so he wants to further develop his program so that the data can only be passed on with the consent of the person concerned.
Another question is, of course, that the person concerned can hardly prohibit access to his data, since otherwise the insurance companies would not conclude a contract with him.
And so the chickens are somehow left at the mercy of the fox.
