Both in the States and in Europe, the crisis seems to be accelerating the long-feared events that are finally taking shape and coming to light in these new conditions.
The first of these phenomena is the rediscovery, the unprecedented renaissance of the state combined with a kind of renationalization of the economy.
Indeed, the crisis means a decline in banking and financial institutions, which have close ties abroad while managing a vast amount of the wealth of private households residing in a single state.
This poses an immediate political problem for governments: how to behave towards the affected families, who also represent an enormous mass of voters.
The crisis thus appears global in economic terms, but politically it is almost purely national.
Political internationalism seems to have been sidelined and lost its right to speak: clear evidence of this has been given by the EU, which, being divided into various national and international conflicts, cannot find a common path.
Therefore, everyone now expects the intervention of their own state; Rescue plans, new rules, and above all the distribution of aid funds: since the crisis became more and more serious, only the USA is in the economic position to save itself without outside help.
And in addition to the means, they also have the legitimacy to use them: two prerequisites that should not be overestimated - under certain circumstances - on which no other international organization and no market will be able to fall back in a similar way.
Moreover, the new emphasis placed on the state-national element is perfectly consistent with the increasing importance that has recently been attached in economics to a very closely related sector: territoriality.
Paradoxically, it is precisely now, when we were so convinced that we had long since entered a networked total kingdom, into a kingdom of ever more differentiated technologies, of the immaterial, that we suddenly have to realize how our future is becoming more and more of the will depend on essential material things: water, crops and oil.
While these can certainly all be transported from one place to another in the world, they are nonetheless bound to a narrowly defined piece of earth – a territory.
Therefore, the one who has such a territory has an advantage over another who lives in a cropless, waterless, or oil-free area.
I now come to the second novelty, which, however, requires a brief interlude.
Anyone who says territory, who government, whoever says politics also says leadership.
In this sense, the financial crisis seems to produce two converging phenomena.
