Medicines: never take with fruit juice
Beware of grapefruit, orange and apple juice.
These beverages, which are consumed mainly in the summer due to their refreshing quality and richness in vitamins, can cause serious health problems if taken at the same time as certain essential medications, as they can have an extreme effect on the absorption of these by the body.
David Bailey, a professor at the University of Western Ontario in London, repeatedly points out the risk of packaged and fresh fruit juices in connection with the use of medication. At the 236th meeting of the American Chemical Society in Philadelphia, he sounded the alarm again: A glass of apple, orange or grapefruit juice is enough to reduce the absorption capacity of certain vital drugs to such an extent that they are practically eliminated and thus the health of the patients is endangered.
Grapefruit juice has already been suspected of being responsible for increasing the effects of some drugs, such as antibiotics, anti-asthmatics, cardiovascular drugs, anxiolytics and neurological agents, to toxic levels.
PHARMACEUTICALS AT RISK – The same drug agency warned doctors and patients of the dangers of this mix in a report two years ago, urging them to be careful about what they drink in conjunction with drugs such as diazepane or methadone.
IT&#39;S NOT JUST GRAPEFRUIT - According to the experts, orange juice and apple juice also contain substances that can inhibit the drugs.
The list of active ingredients inhibited by fruit juices is long.
Hence the appeal from Michele Carruba, director of the Università Statale di Milano: &quot;Such results are usually immediately forwarded to the various international manufacturers, who are then free to change the consumer information.
