Female students are victims of the high rent prices of up to 900 euros per room
The market for apartments for students knows no crises.
According to the latest research by Sunia, the tenants&#39; union, a single room can cost a student up to 900 euros in Milan, 700 in Florence, 650 in Naples and 600 in Rome.
&quot;This phenomenon has already taken on very serious features. Scores of students are effectively losing their right to study because their families are not able to support them to such an extent&quot; - said Laura Mariani, in charge of Sunia - &quot;in In these cities, the high student demand is causing the market to deform, which has also harmed the other residents.
In addition, most rental offers contain a number of violations: free contracts, missing registrations, no rent limit, unauthorized subletting.
For Sunia, there is a need for extraordinary measures that lead to lower rental prices through a revision of taxation.
A closer look at the study reveals that in Milan a place to sleep in the Brianza district costs about 450 euros; a single room starts at 650 euros (in the Bande Nere area) and ends at 800 euros in the Lambiate, Udine and Fiera area or even 900 euros in the Vittoria area.
In Florence, a bed costs on average 350/400 euros, a room 700.
In Bologna, where students are concentrated in the neighborhoods around the university, 250/280 euros are needed for a bed, 370 to 500 for a single room.
In Rome, the prices in the areas around the university are around 600 euros for a single room, 450 for a bed in a double room.
The rents in the areas around the other universities in Rome are only slightly lower: 550 euros in Ostiense and Cinecittà.
Only those who move to the outskirts can save money: 300 euros for a sleeping place and 450 euros for a single room in Prenestina, Centocelle and similar quarters.
In Naples you need 300-450 euros for a bed, for a room the price ranges from 400 to 600 euros in the most expensive areas, Policlinico, Vomero and Colli Aminei.
In Bari, a bed costs 250-350 euros, a single room at least 350.
Prices are lower in the smallest towns, but they carry more weight in the urban economy.
In the cities where the phenomenon of renting to non-European students is more frequent, such as Perugia, there is even another anomaly: rents 25-30% above the average are requested by foreign students.
Goodbye to the old Paradiso cinema – the cities are closing their historic cinema halls
The historic cinemas are closing because of the preferential multiplex cinemas.
&quot;A city without cinemas is a blind city, like a face without eyes.&quot;
This image, directed by Giuseppe Tornatore, effectively describes what is currently happening in the major urban centers of Italy, as well as in the provinces.
The process of exclusion of the cinemas, which began with the birth of the large multi-screen complexes in the periphery, means in the long run the death of the single-screen cinema in the centre. A process that not only appears inevitable and irrevocable, but also bears the traits of a cultural crime.
Historical places full of memories are mostly affected, &quot;it&#39;s like losing a friend with whom you have traveled a stretch of road full of emotions,&quot; says the director of the film &quot;Nuovo Cinema Paradiso&quot;, who gave him the Oscar and the big one 20 years ago Cannes Prize. It is the story of a suburban cinema and its nostalgia, which consists of living in a cinema world that is probably lost forever.
The figures provided by Anec, the central trade association, speak a clear language: in the last five years, the enormous number of 316 traditional cinemas have had to close; this bill was mostly paid by the cinemas in the big cities: 10 in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 in Turin and 5 in Palermo.
The hardest-hit regions include Emilia-Romagna with 82 cinemas lost, followed by Tuscany at 44 and Lombardy at 41.
This shows that the main culprits are multiplex cinemas, because it is precisely in these three regions that the largest number of these modern cinemas has been registered: Lombardy tops the lists with 195 in the last 5 years, 81 in both the Tuscany as well as in Emilia-Romagna.
&quot;The business has developed in an irrational way&quot;, says Paolo Protti, President of Anec, &quot;although it is useful that new structures are created, the priority is to preserve the existing ones, because a hall closes in of the city, not all of its regular customers are willing to go to a multiplex cinema on the outskirts instead of the old one.
And here the missing budget for the fund of the trade association remains: the debt burden recorded by the state amounts to approx. 10 million euros.
It is a shame from an ethical point of view that the government does not respect the existing laws.
In order to maintain the sector, between 16 and 18 million euros a year would be needed&quot;.
The case of Bologna is interesting, the first Italian city that, because of the fears for the old cinema halls, decided to protect them through an agreement between the municipality and the Anec; it is the first agreement of its kind in Italy aimed at protecting and supporting traditional cinemas, both in the historic center and in the outskirts.
Among the envisaged measures are also tax advantages for the operators of cinemas, as well as advantages for the public in terms of local transport: they will be allowed to drive into the traffic-restricted areas of the center and also park at cheaper parking rates.
&quot;It&#39;s a good initiative,&quot; says Giuseppe Tornatore, &quot;I hope that other cities will follow our example and also come up with new concepts.
Of course, we also need better audio and video equipment to counteract the superpower of multiplexes, because today&#39;s audience is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema has always been an important issue for me: the closure of the &quot;Supercinema&quot; of Baghiera, the place of my childhood and adolescence, was the crucial point that led me to found the &quot;Nuovo cinema Paradiso&quot;, also when I had been toying with the idea for 10 years.
I have lived in Rome for 25 years; when I pass the Rialto or the Quirinale in Via Nazionale, places where I have experienced so many different emotions, I turn to the side so as not to have to look at the dust-covered posters.
Links between politics and &#39;Ndrangheta lead to the arrest of the mayor of Gioia Tauro
&quot;The mayor of Gioia Tauro was willing to adapt the municipality&#39;s decisions to the interests of the Piromalli mafia group.
The accusations made by Calabria&#39;s anti-mafia lawyers against the mayor of Gioia Tauro, Giorgio Dal Torrione, and his deputy, Rosario Schiavone, who were arrested this morning for involvement in mafia transactions, are serious.
Also handcuffed were Gioacchino Piromalli, the elderly intermediary between the clan and the public administration, as well as his nephew: the lawyer, who shares the same name as the clan boss, had already been convicted of involvement in criminal Mafia organizations, back then compensation of 10 million euros.
