A wiretapping operation related to the investigations into the Dal Torrione case revealed a willingness to accommodate the wishes of an entrepreneur known to be a representative of the large group surrounding the Piromalli - thereby making the actions of public administration identical to the interests of this clan .&quot;
When the energy rises from the waves, the big ones suddenly appear
It&#39;s a never-ending source of cash that covers over 70% of the planet&#39;s surface and it&#39;s only now that the world&#39;s big energy companies seem to be realizing this.
Waves, currents and tides are the new renewable energy sources that everyone is now looking to, and also seek to occupy, such as giants like Chevron.
The possibility of extracting energy from the movements of the sea has been considered and studied for 70 years; not coincidentally, these studies have intensified considerably since the first oil crisis.
When the price of oil collapsed around 1980, people forgot about the idea of ocean energy, but now environmental organizations and the increased oil price are pushing for new impetus in this sector.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimates that 15% of the world&#39;s energy needs could be covered by the energy generated by ocean waves.
This would be twice the energy currently produced by nuclear power plants.
There are also currents and tides.
Giants Attack.
The first company to bet on ocean energy is Enersis, which signed a contract in 2005 to build a power plant in northern Portugal.
When this news was published, it appeared to be a revolutionary move.
Two years later, more and more companies from the traditional energy sector are relying on marine energy generation.
&quot;Chevron is studying these technologies&quot; - a spokesman for a company known to the US giant told The Wall Street Journal - and is considering the possibility of working with us.&quot;
This involves obtaining approval from the American Energy Commission, which is necessary to start a project off the coast of Alaska.
This is a sign that should not be underestimated, especially when you consider that the USA is still producing oil in Alaska and that President Bush only recently started plans for new drilling.
In addition to Chevron, New York-based Verdant Power Inc. and New Jersey-based Ocean Power are also investing in the new industry; Even if the details are not known, observers speak of an increasing interest.
Technologies still in need of improvement.
Experts speak of a technology that is still in its infancy, not least because the last doubts on the part of environmentalists have not yet been clarified.
So far, projects like the one in Portugal and Scotland are of rather small dimensions and do not seem to cause any serious ecological problems.
However, to produce energy on a large scale requires technologies with far greater environmental impact.
There are several possibilities: Ocean Power, for example, uses a system of interconnected buoys.
The thrust of the waves, which moves the buoys up and down, is converted into hydraulic pressure inside the floats via pistons and cylinders.
This drives a turbine, which in turn drives a generator.
The current is then sent to the coast via underwater lines.
So far, there are four planned plants of this type, which are just waiting for government approval. Part of the energy obtained could also be used for military installations.
Meanwhile, Verdant Power is already producing energy for a department store and parking lot using subsea turbines in New York&#39;s East River.
The water movements during the tide drives the turbines, which feed the generator through the resulting rotary movement.
According to Verdant, a long line of potential clients is already waiting for the necessary authorizations to use these energy sources.
First the waves, then the tides.
According to the Institute for Power Generation Research, the potential that lies in the tides deserves special interest at the moment.
Although an irregular phenomenon, tides are more predictable than wind currents, solar radiation and even waves, and are therefore a more reliable source of electricity.
It is precisely tidal energy that prompted states such as New York, Maine and Alaska and other coastal states to invest 7.5 million dollars in 2008 - for 2009 up to 35 million are already planned.
